"""
Phase 2: AI-driven framework updates.

Flow (called from executor._run when the user enables AI on an upload):
  1. dry-run already told us which steps are undefined
  2. build a context pack: uploaded feature + old feature + existing Steps/Page java
  3. ask Azure OpenAI for COMPLETE updated java files
  4. javac them into an isolated classes dir (compile errors go back to the
     model for up to AI_MAX_FIX_ROUNDS repair rounds)
  5. return {rel_path: code} + the classes dir; the executor prepends that dir
     to the classpath so the JVM uses the new classes WITHOUT touching the
     framework. Commit-to-framework only happens after a green run.
"""
import re
import subprocess
from pathlib import Path

import requests

from . import config

FILE_RE = re.compile(r"===FILE:\s*(.+?)\s*===\s*\n(.*?)===END===", re.S)
PKG_RE = re.compile(r"^\s*package\s+([\w.]+)\s*;", re.M)
CLS_RE = re.compile(r"(?:public\s+)?class\s+(\w+)")

SYSTEM_PROMPT = """You are a senior Java test-automation engineer maintaining an enterprise
Cucumber + Selenium + TestNG framework (package root com.nbc).
Your job: update step-definition and/or page-object classes so a modified Gherkin feature executes.

Rules:
- Keep existing package declarations, imports, naming and coding style.
- REUSE existing methods, steps and locators wherever possible; change only what the feature requires.
- Cucumber matches steps by their exact sentence text - annotation strings must match the feature lines exactly.
- NEVER invent application locators. If a genuinely new UI element is needed, copy the locator style
  of the provided Page class and mark it with: // TODO QA: verify locator
- RADIO BUTTONS and CHECKBOXES: first REUSE any existing radio/checkbox helper method shown in the
  context (the framework usually already has one - search the catalogs before writing your own).
  If you must write new selection code, enterprise UIs typically hide the real <input> under a
  styled span/label, so a plain input.click() often does NOT register. The pattern below is
  ILLUSTRATIVE - use your own appropriately-named variable and the REAL locator, do not copy the
  example variable name literally or leave any part of the statement incomplete:
    WebElement rb = driver.findElement(locator);
    if (!rb.isSelected()) {
        try { rb.click(); }
        catch (Exception e) { ((JavascriptExecutor) driver).executeScript("arguments[0].click();", rb); }
    }
    // verify: if still !rb.isSelected(), click the associated <label> (label[for='<id>'] or the
    // input's parent label) and re-check - selecting a radio must END in isSelected()==true.
  For a radio identified by its option text (e.g. selecting "Court Order"), prefer a locator that
  targets the input via its value/id, or the label with that exact visible text, following the
  Page class's existing locator style.
- DROPDOWNS (Selenium Select / <select> elements): NEVER use selectByVisibleText(rawValue) with the
  literal step parameter verbatim - the real option text's exact casing/spacing is usually unknown
  at generation time (e.g. a feature step says "yes" but the real dropdown option is "Yes" or "YES"),
  and an exact-match selectByVisibleText throws NoSuchElementException on any mismatch. Always
  generate a case-insensitive, trimmed match against the REAL options instead:
    Select sel = new Select(driver.findElement(locator));
    String target = value.trim();
    boolean matched = false;
    for (WebElement opt : sel.getOptions()) {
